This Java program takes an XPath expression as input and attempts to convert it into a UiSelector for use in Android UI testing (typically with UIAutomator).  It's important to understand that a complete and perfect conversion isn't always possible; XPath offers significantly more expressive power than UiSelector. This program provides a best-effort conversion for common XPath patterns.

```java
import android.support.test.uiautomator.By;
import android.support.test.uiautomator.UiSelector;
import android.util.Log;

import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class XPathToUiSelector {

    private static final String TAG = "XPathToUiSelector";

    public static UiSelector convertXPathToUiSelector(String xpath) {
        // Simple XPath patterns handling
        xpath = xpath.trim();

        //Handle // tagname[attribute='value']
        Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile("//([a-zA-Z0-9]+)\[@([a-zA-Z0-9]+)='([^']+)'\]");
        Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(xpath);

        if (matcher.matches()) {
            String tagName = matcher.group(1);
            String attribute = matcher.group(2);
            String value = matcher.group(3);

            UiSelector selector = new UiSelector().className(tagName).attributeContains(attribute, value);
            Log.d(TAG, "Converted XPath to UiSelector: " + selector.toString());
            return selector;

        }else if(xpath.startsWith("//")){
            //Handle //tagname  case -  only className
            String tagName = xpath.substring(2);
            UiSelector selector = new UiSelector().className(tagName);
            Log.d(TAG, "Converted XPath to UiSelector: " + selector.toString());
            return selector;
        }
        // Handle more complex scenarios if needed...  (This is where you would add more sophisticated pattern matching)
        else {
            Log.w(TAG, "XPath conversion not supported: " + xpath);
            return null; // Or throw an exception
        }
    }


    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String xpath1 = "//android.widget.TextView[@text='Hello']";
        String xpath2 = "//Button[@resource-id='com.example.app:id/myButton']";
        String xpath3 = "//TextView";


        UiSelector selector1 = convertXPathToUiSelector(xpath1);
        UiSelector selector2 = convertXPathToUiSelector(xpath2);
        UiSelector selector3 = convertXPathToUiSelector(xpath3);


        // Example usage in UIAutomator (requires Android testing framework setup):
        // UiObject2 object1 = uiDevice.findObject(selector1);
        // object1.click();


    }
}
```

**To use this code:**

1. **Android Studio Setup:** You need to have an Android project set up with the Android testing framework (including UIAutomator).  Add the necessary dependencies to your `build.gradle` file.

2. **Import:**  Import the necessary classes ( `android.support.test.uiautomator.By`, `android.support.test.uiautomator.UiSelector`, `android.util.Log` ). Note that the `android.support` package is deprecated, newer projects should use `androidx`. The equivalent imports would be `androidx.test.uiautomator.By` and `androidx.test.uiautomator.UiSelector`.  Update accordingly based on your project setup.

3. **Limitations:** This code handles only some basic XPath expressions.  More complex XPath expressions (e.g., those involving predicates with multiple conditions, axes, or functions) would require a significantly more robust parsing and conversion mechanism.  You might need to use a full-fledged XPath parser library if you need support for complex expressions.  Consider using a dedicated UI testing library if dealing with elaborate UI structures.

4. **Error Handling:** The code includes basic error handling (logging a warning if the XPath is not supported).  You might want to add more robust error handling (exceptions, etc.) for production use.

5. **Testing:**  Thoroughly test the conversion with various XPath expressions to ensure it works as expected for your use cases.

Remember to replace placeholders like `com.example.app:id/myButton` with the actual resource IDs from your app.  The `main` method shows how to use the `convertXPathToUiSelector` function; you would integrate this into your actual UIAutomator test scripts.

